Adjust rack to top position and preheat broiler to 500 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil. Slice @Fresh Mozzarella{8%ounce} into thin rounds. Pat @Chicken Breast Strips{20%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}, then season all over with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and half the @Tuscan Heat Spice{2%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest later).

Once water is boiling, add @Penne Pasta{12%ounce} to pot. Cook until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve ¼ cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Meanwhile, heat a large drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{2%teaspoon} in a large, high-sided pan over medium-high heat (use an ovenproof pan if you have one). Add chicken and cook, stirring occasionally, until browned on all sides but not yet cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Don't overcrowd the pan—you may want to work in batches so the pieces brown evenly.

Add @Crushed Tomatoes{27.52%ounce}, @Chicken Stock Concentrate{2}, penne, remaining Tuscan Heat Spice, and reserved pasta cooking water to pan; stir to combine. Simmer until sauce has thickened slightly, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in @Butter{1%tablespoon}; season with salt and pepper.

> If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer mixture to a 9-by-13-inch #baking dish{}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @Panko Breadcrumbs{½%cup}, a drizzle of @Olive Oil{1%teaspoon}, and a pinch of salt. Evenly top pasta mixture with mozzarella and panko mixture. Season all over with pepper.

Broil (or bake) pasta until panko is golden brown and sauce is bubbly, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> Keep an eye on dish while broiling. Cool slightly, then divide between plates and serve.